ome (i : Nat)`.\n\nHowever, looking at the context, `opReq` is `Option (Request)`. The `valConsistent` function expects `Option (Request)`s to be mapped to `Option (Nat)`. This suggests that the consistency is defined in terms of the `id` of the `Request`.\n\nLet's assume that `valConsistent` for an array `val` means that for all indices `j`, `val[j]` is `some r` iff `r`'s `id` is `j`.\n- If `val'` is `arr.val.uset i opReq h`:\n  - For indices other than `i`, the elements are the same as in `arr.val`, which are consistent.\n  - For index `i`, the element is `opReq`.\n  - If `opReq` is `none`, then the `i`-th element is `none`. This is consistent if the original `i`-th element was `none`. But if `h` is true, then `i < size`, so the original `i`-th element was `some ...`. This is a contradiction. So `opReq` must be `some r`.\n  - If `opReq` is `some r`, then the `i`-th element is `some r`. For consistency, we need `r`'s `id` to be `i`.\n  - This suggests that `valConsistent` will only hold if `opReq = some (id=i)`.\n\nThis indicates that the problem might be with the definition of `valConsistent` or the structure of the proof.\n\nLet's look at the second case of the `if-then-else` expression for `val'`:\n- `val' := match opReq with | some req => arr._insert req | none => arr.val`.\n- If `opReq` is `none`, then `val'` is `arr.val`. In this case, `valConsistent arr.val = true` by hypothesis. So `sorry` here is a problem.\n- If `opReq` is `some req`, then `val'` is `arr._insert req`. We need to prove `valConsistent (arr._insert req) = true`. This should be provable from `arr : RequestArray`.\n\nSo the issue is with the `sorry` in the `none` case of the `match` expression. We need to replace it with a proof that `valConsistent arr.val = true`.\n\nThe fix would be:\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib\n\ntheorem emptyArrayCoherent : valConsistent (Array.mk []) := by\n  simp [valConsistent]\n```\nAnd then use this theorem in the `none` case.\n\nThe corrected code block would be:\n``